{{short description|A collection of mucus-like organic matter found in the sea}} {{Expert needed|Marine life|ex2=Oceans|reason=Terminological confusion, poorly referenced|date=January 2014}}
'''Sea snot''' or '''marine mucilage''' is a collection of [[mucus]]-like organic matter found in the sea. The substance is described as "jello-like sheets of disease-carrying mucus" that holds a strong presence in the [[Mediterranean Sea]] and has been spreading into farther-flung waters.<ref>{{cite web|author=David Gilson|url=https://www.motherjones.com/blue-marble/2009/10/sea-snot-climate-change|title=Sea Snot: Climate Change Gets Gross|date=October 13, 2009|accessdate=2013-05-20}}</ref>
== Causes == Sea snot forms when globs of [[marine snow]] coagulate into large globs that can span distances as large as 124 miles.<ref name="Dell'Amore">{{cite web|author=Christine Dell'Amore|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2009/10/091008-giant-sea-mucus-blobs.html|title=Giant, Mucus-Like Sea Blobs on the Rise, Pose Danger|publisher=National Geographic|date=October 8, 2009|accessdate=2010-09-24}}</ref> The mucilage has many components, including a wide range of microorganisms including [[virus]]es and [[prokaryote]]s, and [[exopolymer]]ic compounds with [[colloidal]] properties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0007006|title=Climate Change and the Potential Spreading of Marine Mucilage and Microbial Pathogens in the Mediterranean Sea|date=September 16, 2009|publisher=PLoS One|author1=Roberto Danovaro|author2=Serena Fonda Umani|author3=Antonio Pusceddu|accessdate=2009-10-13}}</ref> Sea snot is also produced by [[phytoplankton]] when they are stressed.<ref>{{cite web|author= Xeni Jardin|url=http://boingboing.net/2010/09/24/sea-snot-explodes-ne.html|title=Sea snot explodes near BP spill disaster site, threatening marine ecosystem|date=September 24, 2010|accessdate=2013-05-20}}</ref>
== Effects == A recent increase in the amount of sea snot in the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] and other seas may be the result of [[climate change]]. Warmer, slower moving waters increase the production of sea snot and allow it to accumulate in massive blobs.<ref name="Dell'Amore" /> Sea snot was first reported in 1729 and has long been seen as a nuisance to the fishing industry and coastal populations.<ref name="Dell'Amore" /> Recently, sea snot has emerged not only as a nuisance, but as a major hazard. Globs of sea snot can harbor bacteria such as ''[[E. coli]]'' that threaten maritime flora and fauna as well as humans exposed to contaminated water. It can also coat the [[gills]] of sea creatures subsumed in it, cutting off oxygen and killing them.<ref name="Dell'Amore" />
The [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] created large amounts of sea snot. Scientists are not sure how exactly the spill caused so much sea snot to form, but one theory asserts that the sea snot could have been the result of a massive kill of [[Marine microorganism|microscopic marine life]] creating a "blizzard" of [[marine snow]]. Scientists worry that the mass of sea snot could pose a biohazard to surviving [[marine life]] in the area.<ref>{{cite web|author=Christine Dell'Amore|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2010/09/100916-sea-snot-gulf-bp-oil-spill-marine-snow-science-environment/|title=Sea Snot" Explosion Caused by Gulf Oil Spill?|publisher=National Geographic|date=September 23, 2010|accessdate=2010-09-24}}</ref> It is widely believed that the Sea Snot left by the spill directly resulted in the loss of sealife in the Gulf of Mexico based upon [[Environmental impact of the Deepwater Horizon oil spill#Impacts to marine species#Corals|a dead field of deepwater coral]] 11 kilometers away from the Deepwater Horizion station.<ref>http://www.nature.com/news/2011/110413/full/472152a.html</ref>
